Weather on Easter Island can change dramatically within minutes. Great opportunity to take some epic shots!

Easter Island is so much more than moai. Stunning landscapes and dramatic coasts all around. There are pretty much only two sandy beaches but we had amazing time enjoying both, one of which, a short, rocky walk from this spot, nestled along a massive cliff.

Some of the moai on the Easter Island wear mysterious hats. The hats themselves are around 2.5 meters in diameter, 2 meters high, weighing several tonnes each... to this day the question why and how these were placed on the statues remains unansweredðŸ—¿
Sunset and moai.

Probably one of the most mystical and remote places on Earth. Never thought I could spend hours just looking at any stone figures but getting to know their history in this spectacular scenery is any traveller's dream. A riddle that has not yet been fully solved. A portal to lost civilization. A tropical island battered by rough waves, 6 hours flight from any other land. Very few other places have such immense power to spark thirst for discovery.

It was quite a journey to get from New Zealand to another magical place- Easter Island. Crossed the Date Line for the first time so it was fun to technically arrive to a destination before leaving the origin. A tiny refuge in the middle of Pacific... boy were we in for a treat!

Stunning lakes, mountains, volcanoes, forests, geysers, beaches, waterfalls, glaciers, caves, rivers, mud pools, fiords, valleys or... gorges, like the one pictured... you name it and New Zealand has it. Unforgettable adventures, remarkable setting. Considering that all of this is packed in a relatively small area, the geographical diversity is second to none. And although sometimes "spoiling" with very easy accessibility to the most insane landscapes, the memories of a month spent here are priceless. Kia ora!
Postcard from Wellington!
Took hundreds of amazing shots by the Lake Pukaki as we drove along its shores. Waking up to this view was definitely one of the highlights. Good morning!
Sunset at Lake Tekapo. We had it all to ourselves that evening.

Driving along Lake Pukaki on the way to Mt. Cook was a truly beautiful expierience. We couldn't wish for better weather. Golden slopes, turquoise lake, great visibility of the Southern Alps. Perfect harmony.

Apart from the obvious reasons, I love sunsets for their ability to make even the most ignorant imbeciles stop for a moment, observe and, hopefully, reflect for a minute. It's comforting to think there is still something that so incontrovertibly brings the best in people.
The highest of New Zealand. Aoraki aka Mount Cook.
